<ab><lb n="1"/> <w lemma="ἀθάνατος">ἀθανάτοισιν</w> <w lemma="ὅμοιος">ὅμοια</w> <w lemma="πόρω">πόρες</w> <w lemma="κλυτός">κλυτὰ</w> <w lemma="ἔργον">ἔργα</w> <w lemma="πόλις">πόληι</w> <g ref="#scroll"/> <space extent="3" unit="character" dim="horizontal"/>  <lb n="2"/> <w lemma="ἥρως">ἥρως</w> <w lemma="εὐσεβής">εὐσεβίης</w> <w lemma="θεοτερπής">θεοτέρπεος</w> <w lemma="ἔμπνοος"><unclear reason="damage">ἔν</unclear>πνοος</w> <w lemma="εἰκών">εἰκών</w> <space extent="3" unit="character" dim="horizontal"/>  <lb n="3"/> <w lemma="τοὔνεκα">τοὔνεκα</w> <w lemma="νῦν">νῦν</w> <w lemma="νάω">νάεις</w> <persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Εὐπείθιος">Εὐπείθιε</name></persName> <w lemma="καί">κα<unclear reason="damage">ὶ</unclear></w> <w lemma="πόλος">πόλον</w> <w lemma="ἄστρον">ἄστρων</w> <supplied reason="lost"><space extent="3" unit="character" dim="horizontal"/></supplied>  <lb n="4"/> <w lemma="ψυχή">ψυχὴν</w> <w lemma="ἀναπνέω">ἀμπνεύσας</w> <w lemma="ὅτε">ὅτε</w> <persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Μάρτιος">Μαρτίο<unclear reason="damage">υ</unclear></name></persName>  <w lemma="ἦμαρ"><unclear reason="damage">ἦμαρ</unclear></w>  <w lemma="παίζω">ἔπαιζ<unclear reason="damage">ε</unclear><supplied reason="lost">ς</supplied></w>  <lb n="5"/>  <space extent="3" unit="character" dim="horizontal"/>    <space extent="3" unit="character" dim="horizontal"/>    <space extent="3" unit="character" dim="horizontal"/>  </ab>
</div>
         <div type="apparatus">
            <p>l. 1,  <foreign xml:lang="grc">ΕΡΓ</foreign> damaged</p>
            <p>l. 2,  <foreign xml:lang="grc">ΕΝΠ</foreign> damaged</p>
            <p>L.3: <foreign xml:lang="grc">ΑΙ</foreign> damaged. Letters: after <foreign xml:lang="grc">Κ</foreign>, the shadow of a triangle (<foreign xml:lang="grc">Α</foreign>, <foreign xml:lang="grc">Λ</foreign>) and then very little space (<foreign xml:lang="grc">Ι</foreign>, <foreign xml:lang="grc">Υ</foreign>, ?<foreign xml:lang="grc">Ρ</foreign>). Perhaps: <foreign xml:lang="grc">Εὐπείθι ἑκ<unclear reason="damage">ά</unclear>[ς] πόλον ἄτων</foreign>
            </p>
            <p>l.4, <foreign xml:lang="grc">ΜΑΡ</foreign> damaged</p>
            <p>In principle the text could have begun on an upper block, but these four lines of verse are complete in themselves.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>No English translation yet (2007)</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>We have no other Eupeithios so far attested at Aphrodisias in the Roman period, but one (? a sophist) honoured in ? the fourth/fifth century ( <ref type="inscription" n="33" target="050120.xml"/>).</p>
            <p>It is standard for the pious to be thought of as inhabiting a special and honoured place; here the idea is carried farther, presenting Eupeithios as god-like.</p>
         </div>
